mplements distributed coordination\n- Uses AtomicBoolean stopping flag for thread-safe shutdown\n- Manages WorkerGroupMember coordination\n- Handles executor service shutdown with timeouts\n\n**ConnectRestServer.java**: Concrete implementation of RestServer\n\n#### 2. Kafka Broker Runtime (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/)\n**BrokerServer.scala** (lines 729-843): Implements comprehensive broker lifecycle with explicit shutdown ordering\n- **shutdown()** method demonstrates reverse-order shutdown pattern:\n  1. Check controlled shutdown settings\n  2. Stop socket server request processing\n  3. Shutdown scheduler (critical: prevents concurrent access to other resources)\n  4. Stop transaction coordinator\n  5. Stop group/share coordinators\n  6. Stop replica manager\n  7. Shutdown alter partition manager\n  8. Close log manager and remote storage\n  9. Stop quota managers\n  10. Final socket server shutdown\n  11. Close lifecycle manager\n\n**BrokerLifecycleManager.scala** (lines 223-307): Manages broker state machine lifecycle\n- **start()**: Sends StartupEvent through event queue\n  - Initializes channel manager\n  - Transitions to STARTING state\n  - Sends broker registration\n- **beginControlledShutdown()**: Graceful shutdown request\n- **beginShutdown()**: Non-blocking shutdown initiation\n- **close()**: Blocks until complete shutdown\n- Event-driven architecture using KafkaEventQueue for thread-safe operations\n\n**KafkaRaftServer.scala**: Combined controller/broker with startup() and shutdown() methods\n- Implements reverse-order shutdown: broker first, then controller\n\n#### 3. Test Framework (test-common/test-common-runtime/)\n**KafkaClusterTestKit.java**: Demonstrates coordinated startup and shutdown of multiple broker/controller instances\n- Uses ExecutorService for parallel startup\n- Implements synchronized shutdown pattern\n\n#### 4. Mirror Maker (connect/mirror/)\n**MirrorMaker.java** (lines 178-226): Multi-herder lifecycle coordinator\n- **start()**: Creates CountDownLatches, starts all herders in try-finally blocks\n- **stop()**: Stops all herders in try-finally blocks, ensuring each herder is stopped even if others fail\n- **awaitStop()**: Waits for all herders to complete shutdown\n\n### Lifecycle Patterns Observed\n\n#### 1. Startup Ordering\nServices are started in dependency order:\n- Herder (manages everything)\n  - Worker (manages connectors/tasks)\n    - GlobalOffsetBackingStore\n    - StatusBackingStore\n    - ConfigBackingStore\n  - REST server (depends on herder being ready)\n\n#### 2. Shutdown Ordering (Reverse Dependency Order)\nServices are stopped in reverse order to their startup:\n- REST server (stops accepting requests first)\n- Herder (stops managing work)\n  - Worker (stops connectors/tasks)\n  - Backing stores\n  - Status/Config stores\n\n#### 3. Error Handling Patterns\n- **Try-finally blocks**: Ensure shutdown code runs even if errors occur\n- **CoreUtils.swallow()**: Catches exceptions during shutdown to continue with remaining components\n- **Utils.closeQuietly()**: Safe resource cleanup\n- **CountDownLatches**: Coordinate multi-component startup/shutdown\n- **AtomicBoolean flags**: Track shutdown state in thread-safe manner\n\n#### 4. Graceful Shutdown\n- **Timeouts**: Workers use TASK_SHUTDOWN_GRACEFUL_TIMEOUT_MS (default 5000ms)\n- **Hooks**: Register shutdown hooks that trigger stop() on JVM exit\n- **Controlled shutdown**: Brokers support controlled shutdown mode before forceful termination\n- **State transitions**: BrokerLifecycleManager uses state machine (RUNNING → PENDING_CONTROLLED_SHUTDOWN → SHUTTING_DOWN)\n\n#### 5. Thread Safety\n- **Volatile variables**: For cross-thread visibility\n- **Event queues**: Single-threaded processing with queued events\n- **Executor services**: Shutdown gracefully with timeouts\n- **Synchronized blocks**: Protect concurrent access\n\n### Key File References\n\n**Connect Lifecycle Chain**:\n1. Connect.start() → herder.start() → (worker.start() → rest.initializeServer())\n2. Connect.stop() → rest.stop() → herder.stop() → worker.stop()\n\n**Broker Lifecycle Chain**:\n1. BrokerServer.startup() → BrokerLifecycleManager.start() → multiple component startups\n2. BrokerServer.shutdown() → 11-step reverse-order shutdown sequence\n\n**Mirror Maker Pattern**:\n- Manages multiple Herder instances\n- Ensures all herders start even if one fails\n- Ensures all herders stop even if one fails\n- Uses CountDownLatches for synchronization\n\nThis lifecycle pattern ensures that no service attempts to use resources that have already been shut down, and that all graceful shutdown procedures are completed before the JVM terminates."
